{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "715b10bc",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Opening and Preparing Images\n",
    "\n",
    "The examples in the `generators` section have numerous examples on how to generate artificial images, but ultimately most people will be working with real images obtained from X-ray tomography or serial sectioning.  This tutorial will cover a few different aspects about how to open these images for using a Jupyter notebook, or a Python workflow in general."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d70192e4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Opening a Folder of 2D tif Images\n",
    "\n",
    "### Using ImageJ\n",
    "\n",
    "ImageJ is the ultimate image processing tool kit.  It has many functions and filters for doing quantitative analysis, usually added via plug-ins, but it's also very good at converting between file types and formats.  \n",
    "\n",
    "If you have a folder full of 2D images which are either microscope images obtained by serial sectioning or reconstructions of back projections from a x-ray tomography, then you'll want to convert these into a single `tif` image.  `tif` supports 3D images, so all the individual 2D images can be stacked together into a single file.  \n",
    "\n",
    "This can be done in ImageJ using \"File/Import/Image Sequence\" as shown in the screenshot below. Note that the images must be named with a numerical value indicating its order in the sequence, like \"slice_001.tif\". \n",
    "\n",
    "![Figure1](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5092049/198901662-2d70a8f7-04fe-4a4a-b8cb-8cf41b42cdb3.png)\n",
    "\n",
    "A dialog box will appear asking you about some of the details, which are usually correct by default:\n",
    "\n",
    "![Figure2](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5092049/198901924-62e2be6a-2c31-4246-8bef-1f779ea0a293.png)\n",
    "\n",
    "Finally, you'll want to save this new 3d tiff image, which can be done with \"save as\":\n",
    "\n",
    "![Figure3](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5092049/198902015-5d4197b4-610e-4114-8613-07af6067abe2.png)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d1fa0cd9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Directly in Python\n",
    "\n",
    "If you'd rather not get manually involved, then it's also possible to do this in Python.  The `scikits-image` package comes with a handy funciton for just this purpose.  It only takes a few minutes to get used to how it works:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 44,
   "id": "8c0300d3",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from skimage.io import imread_collection\n",
    "seq = imread_collection(\"../../docs/_static/images/Sample 1/*.tif\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6b2a50de",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now let's inspect the result.  We can see a list of files loaded in the `files` attribute:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 45,
   "id": "e08954a8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "['../../docs/_static/images/Sample 1\\\\Sample 1 Carbonized raw data0000.tif',\n",
       " '../../docs/_static/images/Sample 1\\\\Sample 1 Carbonized raw data0001.tif',\n",
       " '../../docs/_static/images/Sample 1\\\\Sample 1 Carbonized raw data0002.tif',\n",
       " '../../docs/_static/images/Sample 1\\\\Sample 1 Carbonized raw data0003.tif',\n",
       " '../../docs/_static/images/Sample 1\\\\Sample 1 Carbonized raw data0004.tif',\n",
       " '../../docs/_static/images/Sample 1\\\\Sample 1 Carbonized raw data0005.tif',\n",
       " '../../docs/_static/images/Sample 1\\\\Sample 1 Carbonized raw data0006.tif',\n",
       " '../../docs/_static/images/Sample 1\\\\Sample 1 Carbonized raw data0007.tif',\n",
       " '../../docs/_static/images/Sample 1\\\\Sample 1 Carbonized raw data0008.tif',\n",
       " '../../docs/_static/images/Sample 1\\\\Sample 1 Carbonized raw data0009.tif',\n",
       " '../../docs/_static/images/Sample 1\\\\Sample 1 Carbonized raw data0010.tif']"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 45,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "seq.files"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2dc47a4c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "And we can access of the loaded images from the `seq` object as if it were a list:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 46,
   "id": "fd49d883",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 500x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from matplotlib.pyplot import subplots\n",
    "fig, ax = subplots(figsize=[5, 5])\n",
    "ax.imshow(seq[0]);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4cbd1cba",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can convert this list into a 3D image as follows:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 47,
   "id": "1a97353d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "im3d = np.zeros([*seq[0].shape, len(seq)])\n",
    "for i, im in enumerate(seq):\n",
    "    im3d[..., i] = im"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "afa180c4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "And now we can use porespy to visualize it:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 48,
   "id": "5ade9a19",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 500x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import porespy as ps\n",
    "fig, ax = subplots(figsize=[5, 5])\n",
    "ax.imshow(ps.visualization.show_planes(im3d));"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d2b5734a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Convert to Binary\n",
    "\n",
    "In this tutorial we will not do anything to clean or denoise these images, as that deserves it's own tutorial. Here we'll just apply a threshold to convert a boolean with `True` indicating solid (the fibers above) and `False` indicating void.\n",
    "\n",
    "First we need to look at the range of values in the image:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 49,
   "id": "21ccf5f1",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 500x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = subplots(figsize=[5, 5])\n",
    "ax.hist(im3d.flatten(), bins=25, edgecolor='k');"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d3644230",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "From the above histogram we can see that the values span from 22000 to 34000. We can just search for a value which does a decent job of segmenting the solid and void by trial and error:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 50,
   "id": "36e014ea",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 500x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = subplots(figsize=[5, 5])\n",
    "ax.imshow(im3d[..., 0] < 30000);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1e15a684",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Because the image is noisy the result is not perfect.  But let's apply this threshold to the entire image now, then visualize the 3D stack:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 51,
   "id": "fc509ba8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 500x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "im = im3d < 30000\n",
    "fig, ax = subplots(figsize=[5, 5])\n",
    "ax.imshow(ps.visualization.sem(im, axis=2));"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d90e5cdb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Opening a 3D Stack\n",
    "\n",
    "Assuming that the 2D images have been turned into a 3D image, as described above, it is straightforward to load them:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 52,
   "id": "0dd2f91a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import imageio\n",
    "im2 = imageio.volread('../../docs/_static/images/Sample 1.tif')\n",
    "ps.imshow(im2, axis=0);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a842b85a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Saving a 3D Image\n",
    "\n",
    "Once you have created a nice image that you want to save, perhaps for visualization in Paraview, you can also use the `imageio` package:\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "imageio.volsave('my image.tif', np.array(im, dtype=np.int8))\n",
    "```"
   ]
  }
 ],
